Here is the actual secret for creators who want to make money. 
It’s very much similar to how ads run on television networks. Think about all your favorite channels on TV. Because there is such interesting programming, and content on that channel, a brand who has to decide where to put their advertising dollars will say wow a lot of people love watching X Network because there’s so much engaging stuff there, so if we want peoples eyes on our advertising, we will pay for advertising on that channel. 
Brands do not rush to channels where people are just Putting a ton of ads on because nobody wakes up every morning to turn on the TV channel that has ads. 

1.Your channel should feel like this engaging life content that people can just consume. This is experiences, entertainment, a lot of your personality, your true self etc. you are a tv channel people should want to watch.

2. Don’t be afraid to be more than one thing. Some people will watch for different reasons, your audience is very diverse based off of their topic interest, and your life is just as diverse. So don’t box yourself into one niche. Think of yourself like a reality show, some people may be more interested in your morning routine, some may love your hair routine, some may be interested in your jokes. Allow your full self to show up because It also opens the different avenues of which you can work with brands.

Hope this helps

Hi. Honest moment.
I am going through an identity crisis.
- because I dont know how to do just one thing. Technically I have Koi and a full time job, but my identity was always around being a multi-hyphenate with fifty million things. I got a high from it. Now I do just one thing outside of work and I am struggling. My thoughts keep coming up with new ideas, but I pause them and focus in. I am more efficient, its best for me…but my identity is a lil shaky.

Who am I when I focus. Thats the new question I am deeply exploring.

Immigrant kids know that we built our identities around scripts our parents could recite after church on Sundays, embellished with sequins of accomplishments, sewn through stories of recognition on the foundation of…”your child isn’t doing as well as mine”. 

Our success was the descriptor we earned as a trophy attached to our name. What we do abroad became our middle name, a gentle nudge of constant pressure…the repayment plan we inherited at immigration.

Our wins were the opening conversations for which aunties sealed their approval of our existence and our pre-marital resume of which could be paraded…at church on sundays.🤪

This year I am examining me without…well being me. You know. 🤷🏾‍♀️

Entrpreneurs, listen up, save this post and read it everytime you feel insecure.

Having no experience in something is your differentiator not your weakness.

1. I worked in advertising for 10+ years and have never taken a marketing class in my life.

2. I built a candle brand and still don’t even know how candles are made, or have ever made one. 

3. I grew a jewelry brand in less than 6 months BY MISTAKE, and knew nothing about jewelry or how it even worked.

4. I have also never in my life written a business plan. (Check back for whether thats a good or bad thing).

5. I am opening my first store in Chicago this may and have no idea what I am doing. I actually dont.

So how do I do it?

Simple.

I confidently say I don’t know things. I will always proudly say “oh I know nothing about this”…but thats always the start line…NOT the finish line, or the excuse, or the insecurity. 

THEN I DO THE WORK TO GO AND OPEN MYSELF UP TO LEARN!!!! I will study everything. I look things up. I ask anyone who will answer. I approach my lack of knowledge with excitement.
I don’t lean on the crutch of “I need a mentor”. 

You don’t need a mentor as a savior if u arent already doing the work (Myleik-ism). 

Hustle, curiosity, consistency and audacity.
That is all u need.

Do you know what’s super interesting. We are taught to protect our boundaries around our happiness, joy, mental health, but not a lot of conversation is had about protecting your creative boundaries. 

I’ve come to notice that I am my most creative when I limit how many people I speak to. When I limit how many outings I have. When I refine the types of people interact with. And it really started to beg the question of how are you protecting your creativity in your every day interactions. What are you looking at on social? is it distracting, is it mental clutter? Is it leading you to ask the wrong questions, or are you looking at things that continue to inspire you that show you the world in different ways that show you photos in different angles that make you wonder “Why the hell did they make that?”

That is creative exercise. 

To be your most creative, You have to literally strip the world around you and build a cocoon that literally fosters your creativity. The things I listen to, the books I read. I will live and breathe Rick Rubin when I need to be in my creative pocket because that is who fuels me. That’s who gives me the audacity, I will look at some of the best artist online who create really stunning visuals ( @tezza.barton , @nishajohny ) . I will watch the stories and listen to the words of people who exist on this app to literally create people like @hiaj , etc who literally make this place a happy energy again. 

So take a look around you inside of you and and who you’re following and ask yourself are you protecting your creativity?

I dont know who needs to hear this but…

1. If someone watches your stories all the time and doesn’t follow you, they aren’t “lurkers” or haters. I love to go to Hermes all the time to see whats new, but I never buy.

2. It is possible to be friends/support people offline and not follow them online. Remember social media is very new, how you show love and support isnt always digital.

3. Don’t ever ask someone why they unfollow you. Its weird. 

4. Post whatever you want, no one cares about you that much. You are overthinking it. The voices in your head are the whispers of your trauma. Its safe here.

5. Unfollow and re-follow people often. And do that in real life too. Align what you see with the phase of life you are in. 

6. Its impossible for everyone who follows you to see all your content. When you sit in traffic, do you see/pay attention to every single car?
Its crowded here.

*TRIGGER WARNING* - this isnt the Ghana you have recently seen on social, not the Ghana that makes you want to buy a ticket, party till 6am and get your hair braided for $25 so you can tell everyone on tiktok. 

On the flip side,  this is the Ghana you have probably seen on foreign media told through a lens of “help me”, “save us” , “only $1 a month”. The kind that chokes you with gratitude for a few minutes until you get distracted by another first world problem. 

Sadly, when you read this, the mental colonialist within us will want to pacify the discomfort of the images through the instant desire want to donate to James, or send him shoes, or school pencils or money. But this post is about a larger issue. It isn’t something I am doing to save James, but a mirror to the community that looks at this everyday and looks away. This is my attempt to paint a picture. To humanize the issue and to make us uncomfortable.

I admit I am not the authorized voice to tell this story because I am a big user of plastic and always thought recycling was a problem for developed nations whose leaders ensured they had constant electricity and running water.

But anyway…

I met James today while shooting. He is the son of a fisherman who was extremely proud of the skill he had inherited from his dad. He wore it on his chest and showed me the nets he had secured. He was a little sassy one who insisted I work the ropes if I was going to shoot on his dads boat. 

It was cute until I wasn’t moving fast enough and he helped me in between disaproving giggles. Minutes later his dad summoned us to help finish pulling in the net they had been pulling for the last hour.

The pull is a communal effort. Between song, dance, hope and monetary possibilities. They move in synchrony. Command. Move. Pause. Pull.

As they unravel the net you see the pessimistic hope that maybe just today, the reality of pollution in Ghana would have eased its grips on the community, their livelihood and James’ future.

No. Such. Luck

My life started in the studio, Art has been an integral part of my life. Creating visuals and storytelling has been the one thing that brings my life pure purpose. On this weeks episode of, I’m going through an identity crisis. I have felt strong and confident in this empire that I am building, but I have felt emotionally shaky. It wasn’t until I had a conversation this weekend with a college friend who is also an immigrant that it all made sense. As an immigrant, your entire existence is tied to who has given you permission to exist in this country. When you come here, your first visa says what school you go to, that visa most likely expires the day you walk across the stage. Every time you re-enter this country, you hold a piece of paper that tells the immigration officer that you are here because you’ve been granted permission by an establishment. Once you graduate and are lucky enough to get a job. The name of that company is stamped in your passport. Your ability to stay in the country depends on the constant anxiety of if they still want you. So then imagine what happens when you aren’t, “wanted anymore”. Your existence is crumbling. Many people have reached out and said, at least you have KHOI but what I’ve had to toy with, is with the fact that, for the first time I exist without a mega name as my permission to be in this country. I am my only permission to be in this country. The brand I am building is my existence. And so while I build my own, I’m also surrendering to the fact that I am struggling, I am going through the worst identity crisis I ever have been. I’m quiet more on here Because I don’t know how to show up when I don’t know who I am anymore.

A love letter to the stubborn entrepreneur. 

People will call you crazy. People will try to steer you into the brand that they are used to. Stand your ground and lean into your purpose. 

Everybody will question you to the point where it gives you anxiety to exist in the exact space that built up your brand, but stick to it. 

Don’t try and get people to affirm your ideas, the  real ones get it. Don’t just give you a customer what they want, give yourself fuel for your soul, give your creativity a chance to be different . 

Always remember nothing u do will make sense, and it doesn’t have to. Hire the people that will help you make it make sense. Devote yourself to quieting down your reflex action to people please. 

If somebody tries to tell you to become something that they are used to remember that brand building does not happen overnight. It happens over time. 

And one day, just one day you’ll walk up to a big shiny building and you’ll be handled a set of credentials that say New York fashion week Designer and you will spend an entire day speaking to some of your dream publications and some of your editor idols.

Story time. 
Although I studied art in high school, I had only ever done painting and drawing. When I got to Wooster, I struck up a friendship with then senior @deedreturner and she invited me to her campus house one weekend.
Long convos led to me showing her my artwork and she tried to convince me to study art again. I had no interest in painting or drawing anymore so she called her housemate Elena and made me show her my work.
Elena thought I was too talented to not do art anymore so told me about photography. It was an incredibly hard class to get into and only had 10 slots every other semester.
She personally emailed the chair of the department, Bridget Milligan and told her about me. I was given a slot in the class (two weeks before registration opened).

I ended up majoring in Photography and got my bachelors degree in film photography with Bridget as my advisor. When I received “honors” in my senior thesis, she wrote me a letter and said “one day I will brag to people that I knew you”. 
🥹Teachers will always hold a dear place in my heart. 

I never shot much once I graduated simply because I dont like people posing for photos. I like random captures and candids and I enjoy doing it for fun.

Today I went back to my love, with the creative team I have grown to adore!
Full circle. Hayet the artist. Hayet the photographer. I always honor those who looked out for me and spoke my name in big rooms.
